result.adr_address: Place Charles de Gaulle, 75008 Paris, France
result.formatted_address: Place Charles de Gaulle, 75008 Paris, France
result.name: Arc de Triomphe

reviews.text: Beautiful, majestic, and a must visit landmark in Paris! The carvings are very intricate, and there are 4 big ones on the faces of the legs of the arch. I highly recommend going up, though the climb is up and down a narrow spiralling staircase (though an elevator is available). From the top, you can see the Eiffel Tower and the surrounding neighborhoods very clearly. If you enjoy photography, the streets that branch out in all directions from the arch makes for incredible shots. Budget 30-60 minutes for your visit, more if you spend more time taking photos.

What a view! We had young kids with us and it was very late in the day so I didn't get much chance to read any info but there was lots of info on the walls inside (near the top). The view outside was fab, we saw sunset whilst up there too which was so cool. Will definitely go again and try to take in some more of the history around the monument

Great place, well worth a visit. Can pay to go into it too. It's about £12 each,  but you will have to climb the stairs.. all 180 plus of them and that's to the room with some history and original bits of stone. It's up another few flights to get onto the top. Will worth it though,  great views and can watch the traffic below on that manic roundabout.

This was a very cool piece of landmark for Napoleon to make in remembrance of his soldiers and all those who perished. I loved going up to the top to take pictures of Paris.  The souvenir shop has many cool items as well. I highly recommend this historical landmark. Don’t miss it!

It's a really cool piece of history that just sits there on a roundabout! I highly recommend visiting this monument and going up it. It's a lot of steps to get up there but the view will be worth it. Nice gift shop and tourist information is at hand. The place can get busy so it may be worth visiting during the day. A good photo opportunity. Recommend

result.name: Sacré-Cœur

reviews.text: A beautiful basilica with amazing views. Due to government laws shutting down most tourist attractions, we only got to view the outside of this iconic building. It is breathtaking. Please be mindful though of your personal belongings, as it is a haven for pickpockets and young black men and women putting string on your arm and try to charge you €5 for it!!! Just do not let these people ruin your holiday, security is needed for that area to protect the vulnerable.

The design is eclectic and to the people of Paris, a symbol of crushed rebellion in the past, thus also a source of shame. It's a beautiful church and entry is completely free. You should wear religiously appropriate and modest clothing if you wish to enter. The interior of the central dome is quite majestic, there are beautiful stained glass windows and gilded murals on the walls. Also offers an excellent view of Paris.

It's a peaceful place, beautiful architecture. For 10€ you can buy a big candle to light if you want and for 2€ a small one. There's also a notebook for visitors to write about their visit. There's a souvenir shop inside. When you exit the metro station,the church is to your right and straight ahead. It's a five minute walk to reach reach the start of the hill where the church is.

Pro tip: find out when the sunset is and time your visit to a half hour or so before hand. The Eiffel Tower puts on sparkling lights at the top of each hour after sunset as well, so you’ll catch an amazing view of the city and great pictures, especially in the small adjacent park with benches to the immediate south west of the basilica. Highly recommend timing your visit with a mass service as well, it’s well worth spending a few hours at the top of the hill.

Beautiful place. We came for a 6 pm mass and vespers on a Monday night, and it was a very special feeling. Gorgeous depiction of Christ in the main dome, and incredible views of the city from here. Worth going out of your way for it, you won’t regret it. We walked up a long flight of stairs on the east side, only to realize later that there is a funicular at the front side of the basilica to climb the steep hill. Worth keeping that in mind especially if 6 or so flights of stairs seems a bit much for you.

Wonderful destination in Paris. The building is magnificent and huge. Everything inside carries a lot of meaning and beauty. Down in the crypt, you can see a beautiful exhibition that mixes the antique with the new by using projections. It's also possible to go up to the dome for 7€ and see Paris from the very top of the building. 

The surroundings of Sacré Cœur are also filled with life and the very best of the Parisian culture.

result.name: Louvre Museum

reviews.text: Absolutely in love with this place. It is huge so I would recommend spending a day or two if you really wanna go through everything. wasn’t too crowded overall except around the Mona Lisa where it was a stampede. There is something for everyone here, it ranges in different time periods and art forms. It surpasses anything we have in Canada in terms of an art museum.They have cute gift shops all around which is convenient. I came from Canada to visit and got the membership which I would recommend considering it was almost the same price as single admission and the line was shorter.

Only downside is that it is too big! Easy to get lost in there. You can use days in there. Had I know it was that big I would have used four days instead of one. One day per floor would cover it nicely. Amazing experience at a very low price. Would love to come visit again.

Absolutely in love with this place. It is huge so I would recommend spending a day or two if you really wanna go through everything. wasn't too crowded overall except around the Mona Lisa where it was a stampede. There is something for everyone here, it ranges in different time periods and art forms. It surpasses anything we have in Canada in terms of an art museum. They have cute gift shops all around which is convenient. I came from Canada to visit and got the membership which I would recommend considering it was almost the same price as single admission and the line was shorter.

I loved this place. If your are an art lover, this place is a paradise for you. One day is not enough to visit the entire museum. But still you can visit the main attractions including the famous Mona Lisa. 
Guided tours and audio guides are available but with an additional price. I would recommend going with a guide as it will give you a very different perspective about the art and the place.
I have a great experience and highly recommend Louvre Museum for someone who is in Paris and have not been to this amazing place.

This is the greatest art museum in the entire world. Absolutely worth a visit. You could easily spend days here if you took your time to digest all of the works. I feel very special I was able to visit such a great place. The only downside as an English speaker is that most of the information for the art was in French. I like to read them, but I completely understand because it is France and they have no obligation to cater to a foreign language.

result.adr_address: Champ de Mars, 5 Avenue Anatole France, 75007 Paris, France
result.formatted_address: Champ de Mars, 5 Avenue Anatole France, 75007 Paris, France
result.name: Eiffel Tower

reviews.text:
We just loved our visit to the Eiffel Tower. This was our first visit and we were amazed at how big it is. It stands much wider than it looks on the pictures. We suggest you to book the tickets in advance online and must see the Paris City from top. The view is just astonishing. We bought the tickets of 4pm slot so that we can enjoy both day and night scenery from top. 

The second level is a great place to enjoy the view and see the whole of Paris. The elevators are generally very crowded. You can use stairs down to the 1st level. There are a lot of winding stairs in the tower but it was a nice experience. There are several shops and eateries in the tower too. You can buy souvenirs but these souvenirs are more expensive than you might find in the shops across the street so you may want to check other places out as well.

We had heard the stories about the pick-pockets around the Eiffel tower so we were extra careful but we didn't see any incidents.

Good luck :)

Love love love! When it lights up at night and when it sparkles, just magical! Words cannot describe the happiness it brings. Walked to it at night, I still believe that it's better appreciated when you're down on the street rather than on the Eiffel tower. Nice and quiet at night as well.

Security was fairly quick and easy to get through. I wish it was a little more organized when it comes to catching an elevator up or down the tower. Besides that, the size of the tower is breath-taking. They also have a fairly priced gift shop. If you're willing to deal with all the tourists, this will be worth it. Definitely, should put this on your bucket list.

Magnificent❤ It is more attractive at night. The lights of the tower as well as the City lights will take your breath away. You can enjoy watching from afar or better yet on a closer look. I visited the area the next day and wandered alone. It was great and peaceful, and yet again  it's true indeed that it's better to experience it with your loved ones. Who wouldn't want a nice stroll with someone holding your hand? Right? 🥰

Enjoy Paris! ❤

Paris is one of the most desirable and popular travel destinations in the world thanks to its stunning architecture, its wealth of art and culture and its exquisite gastronomy that will leave you feeling blissful (if not a few pounds heavier!).

No matter what time of year you visit, Paris will be sure to enamour and enchant with its picture-perfect landscapes and world-class museums. Whether you visit Paris for a day or a week, you’ll be left longing to return to explore this magical city even further.

Read on to discover why Paris is such an enthralling city, why it’s so famous, and what sights and scenes are must-sees when visiting the City of Light and Love.

result.name: Luxembourg Gardens

reviews.text:
I can not believe this is a free park for everyone. It is huge and beautiful and when I visited I saw students studying on the lawns and having picnics. Living their best lives. Honestly, I wish I could stroll out of my house and head to this park to study and eat with friends.

There are lots of free chairs all around and it really is well kept and clean.

Very cool to have visited one of the lesser touristy spots in Paris. 
I had met someone who knew the area well and showed me around and explained some of the history of the area. It was also a nice break in the day from walking around the city. 
Such a memorable experience that I will never forget.

I live nearby and every morning take my dog here. Now that it’s winter most trees are without leaves. The flower beds are constantly updated throughout the year and the gardens are kept in pristine condition. The area for dogs is large although they must be leashed at all times. The pond in the center is beautiful and in the spring/summer it’s enjoyable to watch children launch their boats. Considered a jewel of Paris and it is.

Was a wonderful place to spend a cold but sunny lunchtime.  Sitting in the chairs enjoying a meal while watching children with their boats on the pond.  And then a nice stroll around.  There are free public bathrooms here if needed.

Beautiful gardens, fountain/pond area, and architecture.  There are kids having fun all around... playing with the sailboats in the fountain, as well.  There is a nice playground for the little ones, too.  Like the rest of Paris, it is well laid out, well thought out from an architectural consideration.

result.adr_address: 1 Rue de la Légion d'Honneur, 75007 Paris, France
result.formatted_address: 1 Rue de la Légion d'Honneur, 75007 Paris, France
result.name: Musée d'Orsay

reviews.text: This museum was quite nice. Good layout and diversity of pieces. We got there around 11:30am and maybe waited 10 min in line. They moved the quantity of people quickly and the people working there were nice and polite. They had the art sectioned off so it was easy to walk through and know what you had and had not seen while still moving forward in a full circle. Would recommend to anyone on a trip to Paris.

Worth the lines and crowds (we went on a free day).  The museum itself is awesome, and their collection is wonderful. Big name artists as well as others I was not familiar with.  Wear comfortable shoes as most of the floors are stone.

Another great museum to see once in your life. They had a very nice Van Gogh exhibit while we were there that I really enjoyed. Also their sculptures on the second floor were lovely. 

What catches your eye the most though is that gorgeous clock in the center of it all. Since this place used to be an old train station. 

Lines weren't too long and the crowds were manageable. I was really impressed with how organized they were, every room is numbered so you can check it off your map once you've seen it.

Just like the Louvre you will have to pass security beforehand.

Exceptional museum. Amazing paintings and sculptures, plus furniture . The building is outstanding with views across the river. Great cafe for coffee and cake. Some of the exhibits were outstanding. Quieter than the Louvre. A little gem.

Quick tip - the top floor has some great views of Paris, but they don’t give great pictures. If it’s not too busy, just take a few minutes without your phone and take it all in. This is one of my favorite museums on earth. The impressionists are spectacular, some of the most beautiful paintings on earth are housed here - not to mention the building itself having a wonderful aesthetic to it. I personally would recommend spending more time here than in the Louvre, but make sure to get a good guide!! They rent audio guides for €5 each but they are really just a single piece at a time. Worth having someone knowledgeable take you through and give you some big picture history, contextual information, and inter-artwork info on how art movements grew and inspired each other. 10/10

result.formatted_address: Place de la Concorde, 75001 Paris, France
result.name: Tuileries Garden

reviews.text:
This shot is a very common one to see if you’ve ever looked into visiting Paris. Located between the Louvre and the Place de la Concorde it offers a large open space to sit back and enjoy the views. Originally it was a private garden when the Louvre was all closed off but now it currently serves as a gathering place for tourists and locals. Unfortunately during the winter they do not turn on many of the fountains and the leaves from many of the trees have fallen so it does not have as dramatic of a look. However, while we were there they had a small Christmas festival located here which we really enjoyed. Up until January 5th you can stop by there to try different foods and desserts and buy some souvenirs to take back home. Because this location is so central to many popular landmarks we often found ourselves stopping by the gardens or walking through them on a daily basis. Businesses are also aware of this so it is located just south of many hotels and touring companies. If you book any large group tours and charter bus excursions your meet up point will likely be around here since many of those businesses are located nearby. If you want to be able to fully enjoy the beauty of the gardens then opt to visit in the spring/summer or fall to see the changing of colors and the fountains running. Nevertheless, it is still a place you have to stop by even if just to walk by on your way to another location.
- @wanderingwithustwo

Much more beautiful on a sunny day during summer, but still nice to visit during the off season. Entry is free, the grounds are well kept with plenty of seating, and there is a lot of sculptures to look at. Good for a quick walk between museums or a picnic when the weather permits. Also a great place to take photos as you can get a lot of beautiful buildings in the background.

Great green space in the middle of the city. The plants are often hemmed a bit too much, as what bushes really grow as squares, but I suppose that's the French way of presenting nature ;) In any case, there are some statues, bright flowers in places, and wide walking space areas. Some of the grass areas are used by fitness groups and picnics, so it is quite social and useful, all the while contributing to a better air quality, at least doing it's little part toward that!

This is just a magical place. The size and grandeur of the palace and gardens is mind blowing. You need a whole day or more to really explore the land. Could have spent 2 full days just walking around, taking in the sights, getting lost in its beauty and just enjoying space. Be prepared for tons of people.  More people will be there them you think.

Absolutely essential if you are visiting Paris. If you are a tourist, you should make the time to walk through this park that leads you to the magnificent Louvre. 

There was a great winter market when I went in December, although even in the summer, this is a very well done, very peaceful space. Of course, it's completely free and what makes this a majestic space is the statues that are featured across the park space, so make sure this is on your list to visit. Spectacular.

result.formatted_address: 6 Parvis Notre-Dame - Pl. Jean-Paul II, 75004 Paris, France
result.name: Cathédrale Notre-Dame de Paris

reviews.text: What can I say, it is a beautiful place. Neither myself nor my girlfriend are remotely religious but you couldn't help but feel...something, here. The scale of the place is fantastic, the architecture and history is fascinating. I am so glad I got to see it prior to the fire and I am so glad that it is going to be restored, places like this are so important to our culture, to our history that they should not be allowed to just rot.

This is architecture at its finest.  Amazing details.  Beautiful structure.  Just simply breathtaking inside and out... the powerful and spiritual journey is life changing...  the walk into the church that billions have visited over hundreds of years just takes you to a different place.

VISITORS BE AWARE
While visiting the cathedral itself is free.  In order to climb the stairs and go to the top for the amazing views you do have to pay 10€.  I strongly recommended going and reserving your time to climb the top before entering the cathedral.  That way by the time ur done exploring the cathedral (1 - 1.5hrs or less), it will be your time to climb the top.  Most people did not know that and by the time they got to the reservation area all the spots were gone (by 1430).

The stain glass windows are amazing. Outside the architecture is amazing. Some very strange statues. It makes you wonder why there’s a priest holding his own head. Others show babies being killed. The gargoyles are fantastic and watch over Paris. Admission was free which was a plus.

  An indispensable place for lovers of architectural masterpieces. The most famous cathedral in Paris near the river Sena, one of the oldest, was built in the Gothic style between 1163. and 1345. The witness is many events during the tumultuous history of France, an inspiration for writers. When the sun sets up looks like a fairy tale.

  History at it’s finest... I suggest to download the app to schedule your entry time for the tour, this will allow you to save a time slot, but be aware, if you miss your 10 minute window to get in you will have to wait until the next morning to get another opportunity to get in. You may walk into the actual church and see it, but cannot go up to the towers without the reservation.

Stunning architecture and an incredible experience. This cathedral is actually in use and the required silence inside makes the whole experience even more mesmerizing. I was the dork walking and looking up trying to find the gargoyles. You can see them much better on the sides of the church but they are way too high in the front, you might need binoculars. While inside, you can see a model of the church when it was built and read a little about the history. Highly recommended.

Free to go in, but the lines are very long. I wish I have known that you can pay 10 euros 💶 to go to the top of the structure. You can buy the ticket on the side of the building or online. They do close earlier than going into the church. You have to walk in and massive inside. Interesting info and art inside.
I also suggest to come back at night time! 😉

result.vicinity: 6 Parvis Notre Dame - Place Jean-Paul II, Paris

result.adr_address: 8 Boulevard du Palais, 75001 Paris, France
result.name: Sainte-Chapelle

reviews.text: The stained glass windows here are beautiful and incredibly intricate. You can spend a lot of time looking at each one finding small details. The arches too are very well preserved and incredibly colorful. Audio guides are available. When you enter you'll first only be in the smaller room downstairs with some stained glass, but be sure to take the spiral staircase to the upper room where the real majesty is.

One of the most incredible places I have ever been. So much beautiful color. There are seats along the sides of the walls where you can sit and enjoy the stained glass. Would return. Was honestly a breathtaking experience.

Absolutely beautiful! The stained glass windows are breathtaking and full of detail. There are some seats around the edges of the room where you can sit and take it in. We waited maybe 10/15 min in line and once we were in it wasn’t too crowded or busy. Would recommend as Notre Dame is closed for right now.

A magnificent church built in the medieval time by the King of France.  It is now a particularly popular place for tourists as the nearby Notre-Dame Cathedral is close for reconstruction.  The tinted glass large windows all around the walls of the naive depicting the biblical stories are worth of your time and attention.  A must-see attraction in Paris.

The security check process does take a while and there are usually queues but, to say the least, this is worth the wait.

Once you get inside, your breath will be taken away by the sheer majesty of the place. The stained glass is absolutely incredible. I really don’t think pictures can do this justice and the atmosphere is phenomenal too. 

It’s true, that’s all there really is to see in there but it’s worth seeing. In a prime location in the centre of Paris and the staff were helpful enough.

result.adr_address: 33 Avenue du Maine, 75015 Paris, France
result.name: Montparnasse Tower

reviews.text: Undoubtedly the best views in Paris of Paris.  Evening views are just as spectacular as day time. At 59 floors up, the out door advantages can be quite windy. There is glass shelter all around that provides some cover from above too. Well worth the cost.

The view from the top of the building is wonderful. One of the best places to get an overview of the city, with the Eiffel Tower as the protagonist. I also recommend making a visit to see the city at night, it is sensational!
Pretty good. Not very busy so straight to the top. Good views from inside  but climb steps to top observation deck for outside views and full 360°. Glass here too though! Cafe on top inside floor.

With a height of over 200 m definitely one of the top view points in Paris. Open until late ( a bit shorter during winter). Wonderful scenery at night time with the Eiffel tower, which is relatively close. 

The elevator is very fast. At around 21.00h there was no queuing. At the top you can find a small gift shop, an info desk, binoculars, some plastic chairs and some nice animation (3 min.) about the historic development of Paris (looks like one of the binoculars)!

One of the best views of the city of Paris. The tower is located very close to Gare Montparnasse stop. Getting to this place is very easy irrespective of where you are in Paris. The view is from 56th floor but you can actually climb around 50 stairs to the top where there is an open area and even better view. The coffee shop is reasonably priced. The gift shop is average. Overall a great place to visit during dusk to see both light and evening hues of Paris!

result.adr_address: Place du Panthéon, 75005 Paris, France
result.name: Panthéon

reviews.text: Breathtaking experience! The audio guide is very detailed, but it was amazing wandering all around the huge area and humbling to go down into the crypt where all the amazing architects of history lay. Almost overwhelming to wander in the footsteps of so many great souls, and contemplate the hundreds, even thousands of years of events this area witnessed.

Loved this!! As part of the many attractions that the Paris Museum Pass offers, this one was pretty cool. It kind of reminded me of Westminster Abbey in that there’s a tomb where all the important French people got buried. Victor Hugo, Marie Curie, and Voltaire, etc. It’s pretty neat!
Beautiful architecture and building. A great place to visit on a rainy day. Not a wall that is blank. Each wall commemorates some event/person in French history. Also many massive statues.

Lots of history, stunning architecture, not super busy. Got to go to the crypt where Marie Curie and Braille are kept. Close to lots of nice restaurants, short walk from the metro. Great place to go to if it rains. There are benches inside if you want to take a short break. Stunning paintings on the walls, each with its own story.

Impressive overview of the tombs of some of the major characters in French history. There are interesting paintings in the basilica, but do not forget to visit the crypt, where the remains of famous writers like Hugo, Zola and Dumas will await you. A bit expensive, but worth the visit if you are interested in the turbulent history of France.

result.adr_address: Place des Vosges, 75004 Paris, France
result.name: Place des Vosges

reviews.text: Very cozy and beautiful part of Paris. With 300-400 year-old buildings all around, this is for sure a change of scenery. And the house where Victor Hugo lived at for 16 years, very nice museum.

Well one of so famous place in Paris close to Bastille. Lot of tourist for sure but it has to be seen if you also love modern art. Some great art gallery there. Parc in the middle will welcome families and offer a nice break spot. You are some where in the past., smelling a old Paris. It's Magic.

In the summertime you can sit under a leafy tree and watch the world go by, the fountain sparkling and purling in the light. In winter is a quieter more reflective space but still calm and beautiful. Lots of special shops nearby if that's your thing.
Cute little square in the Marre neighborhood. It is where Victor Hugo used to live and write, though his house-museum is currently in renovation
One of the nicest squares of Paris. Visiting it you can imagine the glorious past of the Parisian society

result.adr_address: 77 Rue de Varenne, 75007 Paris, France
result.name: Rodin Museum

reviews.text: Very nice museum of sculptures. It has a famous statue called The Thinker. It’s a nice mini-palace with different interiors and sculptures in every room. The nearby area is also great for walking and they have a cafe on site. Awesome place for great pictures. I highly recommend this place 👌

My favourite museum in Paris. Been here a couple of times and loved it. Small in size as far as museums go but, amazing metal and marble sculptures of Rodin both inside and outside in the gardens. Gates of Hell one of my personal favourites. The features are so well defined and love the emotions they portray. Check it out if you like sculptures.

This was easily one of the top 5 on our trip to Paris. Rodin's work is abundantly displayed throughout the garden and house and allows for a slow, contemplative visit. It was not very busy on the day we visited and if you're able to go when it's expected to be quieter this is highly recommended. Rodin was famously an outsider to the art community for much of his career and his alternative perspective on sacrifice, women, pain, and just humanity in general is here for you to soak up and appreciate. Being able to see his work in person really allows you to get the most out of his very 'evocative' style - most of his work is not precise or strictly realistic and this works incredibly. A must - there are also wild rabbits in the sculpture garden, for a real peaceful and idyllic experience.

There are some very beautiful sculptures on display here, primarily the work of Rodin. The most famous are "The Thinker", "The Three Shades", and "The Gates of Hell", all located in the outside gardens. Inside the main building are smaller ones made of marble or stone and really demonstrate his artistic and carving ability. However this museum may not be for everyone, so I would only recommend coming if you're particularly interested, have a museum pass and the time to spare, or don't mind spending money on entrance tickets.

Loved this museum. It’s a little smaller than some of the other ones but it’s nice that part of it was inside and part of it was outside. The gift shop is a little limited but they had a cool temporary exhibit on top of the Rodin one. The highlight for me would be “The Gates of Hell” and inside they have some cool smaller versions and mock ups of some of the statues. It’s worth seeing.

result.adr_address: Place de l'Opéra, 75009 Paris, France
result.name: Palais Garnier

reviews.text: One of the most beautiful places I’ve seen in all of Paris or Canada. The main room with the picturesque ceilings is breathtaking. It is definitely worth a visit. I bought tickets in advance which I’m pretty sure are the same price at the opera but it saves you waiting in line to buy the tickets. It was a little crowded for my taste but overall an enjoyable experience.

This is a must-see attraction in Paris no matter you are an opera fan or not.  The building is magnificent in and out, more royally and tastefully decorated than a royal palace.  The painting on the ceiling of the main hall is particularly beautiful, and an artistical illustration of music through the best visual arts of the time.  Very impressed!

Yes, go to the Eiffel Tower. Yes, go to the Louvre Museum. Yes, go to the Versailles Palace, but immediately after, you need to visit what is the most shocking building ever. It's not the eldest or the biggest, but it will impress you more than any other. If you are travelling to Paris and you want to give yourself a treat, don't eat in the Eiffel Tower (it is too expensive) or expend the night in fancy hotels, instead try to go an opera play in here. The tickets are not cheap but either expensive, and it's an experience that you won't forget. Try to take your time and enjoy every gallery. Finally, please don't visit the Palais without taking the audio guide, because it deserves, you will learn and makes memories of the place. Enjoy!!!

I've been to Paris several times but this was my first time here. Incredible venue and super regal. We did not see a show here, we just paid for tickets to tour the Palais Garnier. I highly recommend it!
Beautiful opera house. Stunning architecture inside and outside. Went to see an opera and had optima places in a booth for 70euro. Great Parisian experience.

result.adr_address: Pont Alexandre III, 75008 Paris, France
result.name: Pont Alexandre III

reviews.text: Possibly the most beautiful bridge on the Seine river in Paris! The sides are white with gilding, while at each corner sits a massive stone tower with a gilded figure on top. It's an excellent place to take photos from. The view of the surrounding buildings from this bridge is also good but slightly obstructed.
This is an amazing and must visit place in Paris. The view from the bridge is particularly mesmerizing. You get a far view of the Eiffel Tower and the background monument is perfect for photography.

Really nice bridge. If you are in Paris, you need to check out this bridge, take a Foto with Eiffel Tower from bridge. Wonderful bridge with gold statue and more gold elements. Don't forget to go there. You can see more from the bridge.
The bridge is absolutely stunning with very fine statues. Even the lamp posts are stunning. A nice view to the Eiffel Tower too

Great place at night to walk the river and the Eiffel Tower. Not too many people were out the night I went for a midnight stroll. A little windy at night to make sure you bring a coat or cover up if you’re not going straight to a neighboring bar for a glass of wine.

result.adr_address: 2 Allée Adrienne Lecouvreur, 75007 Paris, France
result.name: Champ de Mars

reviews.text:
Take a stroll, have a picnic or simply soak up the spectacular scenery and relax under the shadow the Eiffel Tower at Champ de Mars, one of the most beautiful green spaces Paris has to offer. Surrounding the Eiffel Tower are the Champ de Mars gardens, where you can enjoy a moment of true Parisian life. You can relax, walk, picnic and play in the in the beautiful gardens along with French families who have been coming here for generations.

Enveloping the Eiffel Tower in a cloak of green, Champ de Mars gardens has been charming French families for generations. Its expansive lawns provide the perfect venue for a picnic with an unbelievable view of the Eiffel Tower, while its playgrounds offer an excellent place for weary kids to unwind after a morning or afternoon of sightseeing. Wander through manicured gardens and this remarkable park, relax and savor a moment of true Parisian life.

It's a beautiful stretch of a green park... Take a breathtaking view of it from the Eiffel tower! Would have loved to have had the time to go about it, but perhaps next time? It's huge for sure though. Oh, and I think it would be great to see Champ de Mars at night with all the lights.

Getting up the Eiffel Tower was actually fun! Pretty windy but beautiful scenery. I was amazed by how the elevators and overall design is clever in comparison to how old the tower is. I know it has been renovated but it didn’t loose it’s authentic touch!

I mean, it’s a giant glittering tower in one of the best cities in the world. You pretty much have to experience this at least once.  Sit under the tower (it’s huge by the way... way larger than I ever expected) drink copious amounts of wine, bring snacks, watch sunset. Watch people. Don’t buy trinkets, unless you need trinkets because wow there’s a lot of glowing / blinking Eiffel towers here !
It was well worth the visit and the views are really nice during daytime and evening. I highly recommend visiting this place if you are at the location. The queue line can be very long.

result.adr_address: 8 Avenue du Mahatma Gandhi, 75116 Paris, France
result.formatted_address: 8 Avenue du Mahatma Gandhi, 75116 Paris, France
result.name: Louis Vuitton Foundation

reviews.text: Great place. Modern architecture: combination of glass and steel. Very fashionable. Warm enough in winter and cool in summer. Polite information-service. Very comfortable and well-organized halls.great view from terrace( but it can be cold if the weather is windy in winter, so it’s better to put on your coat). Lifts, stairs and escalators are available. There is a nice cafe in the ground floor

Serene. Beautiful and calm. Perfect place for family trip. Nice recreation fro children. The architectural beauty is an attraction. It's a must visit if you are in Paris. Very nominal charge for entrance. Easily accessible from metro or bus. Horse riding facility is available, but only for members.
This building is just outstanding... Don’t take my word for it, go and see for yourself. If you’re lucky it will have one amazing exhibition on also, which has happened each time I’ve visited it.
5 hours visit! Very beautiful and each time you can see different artist /designer work. Tha place is so beautiful great view. Amazing architecture..
Beautiful space and art. The building itself is a work of art. Incredibly crowded on the weekend, which is to be expected. I would recommend buying timed tickets in advance to avoid the lines.

result.adr_address: 129 Rue de Grenelle, 75007 Paris, France
result.name: The Army Museum

reviews.text:
This is a great museum to visit for those even remotely interested in the part that France played in various wars throughout history. 

The main entrance area to the museum is through a very large, absolutely stunning, albeit bare courtyard. There's a history of the cavalry-man and their armors throughout history which was impressive. There's also a section in the museum dedicated to the history of the part that France played in world War 1 and 2 - this part subjectively was average as it tried to replicate a unique visiting experience with videos and footage but ultimately failed and was quite boring.

There's an additional area dedicated to small scale models of forts in France, which were great fun to browse through.

Very importantly the Napoleon's tomb is located here too. And is on display in a most impressive manner but requires a separate ticket but definitely worth it, even simply to see the grandeur. Overall a great experience

this army museum was very cool to come and see in person because of the central location it is here in the city. it's another can't miss if you're in the area. my only complaint was that it closes a bit early but we did come a little late. you'll definitely want to spend an hour or so here looking around because there is so much inside the walls to see.

This was my fav place in Paris. Military uniforms/armor and weapons are very well looked after. They way armors and knights are put together is overwhelming, you can travel in history and feel the adrenaline run through your veins. 

Napoleon's tomb is magnificent. 

If you go to Paris this place is a must-go

Wow, what a great museum. Lots of armour and uniforms. The section covering Louis IV through 1870 is terrific. Lots of animated maps  showing how the major battles played out, great sections on WW1 WW2 , Napikeon's tomb is very impressive. Lots of English explanations but still worth getting the audio guide.

Wonderful museum detailing the military history of France.  Very interesting with of course a French twist.  Located right next to Napoleon's tomb.  Both are well worth the visit.  There is a cafeteria with a decent selection of not too expensive foods and drinks.   Clean and well maintained toilets are also available

result.adr_address: 75008 Paris, France
result.name: Place de la Concorde

reviews.text: This is a very historical place and the area around is quite nice as well. I was particularly impressed by the inscriptions on one face of the Concorde regarding the Guillotines. It did really bring me to the past in an informative way about how France was during the French Revolution. The place is free to visit and I think you should not leave this out of your itinerary for Paris. Theres also a nice water fountain nearby of Jupiter(?) Which is good to take pics. Recommend everyone to visit!

Be aware that this is essentially an open square in the middle of several intersecting roads, so you need to cross traffic a few times to get into the area. The constant flow of traffic makes this place not the best for lingering too long, and cars will inevitably obstruct your views of things. Nonetheless it has two beautiful fountains, an Egyptian style obelisk, and provides great views in all directions.

Great landmark with good views, though the traffic through here is often heavy, congested. Well-kept touristy area. Tricky crossings as pedestrians. What's great is that it's sometimes converted into a space for events such as with Olympic athletes. Like most places now, for such events security checks are in place so there are lineups, but otherwise things function quite well.
A great place full of history. Tower came from old Egipto and even a King and his family lost their heads there. It is worthy to visit.
Really cool place, you can feel the heart beat of Paris. Well connected with bus to other sights

result.adr_address: Place Georges-Pompidou, 75004 Paris, France
result.name: The Centre Pompidou

reviews.text: The collection of contemporary arts are magnificent.  The featured art exhibition is excellent as well!  As for the building of Centre Pompidou itself, it is not so good in my humble opinion, I am afraid.  It feels more of city shopping mall, instead of an arts venue.  With that said, Pompidou is still a great place to visit if you can spare a few hours.

Pompidou is is an art exhibit and museum...  and it is very interesting. Everything from Picasso to contemporary. Cost is reasonable. Although I know French closing times are strict, ensure that you check the closing times with a couple of people ... to avoid being ushered out "early" ... as we were.

Although the museum is quite extraordinary and has amazing pieces, it's impossible to see the entire place in one day, it's huge! I'd look up artist and exhibitions to see before going. Additionally, I'd definitely recommend to get a map of the place, because it's easy to get lost there.

My favorite museum in Paris. If you enjoy modern art this is a must. The art here is so creative and cool to see. A variety of large and small pieces, some which you can even walk inside of! Give yourself 2-3 hours to explore this place.

nice place to hang out. The exhibitions and library inside are amazing. you can spend an entire day hanging around in that area. There is even a free access video game room there. A must visit for everyone
